com·mu·ni·ty    ( P )  Pronunciation Key  (k-myn-t)<br>
n. pl. com·mu·ni·ties <br>
<br>
1. A group of people living in the same locality and under the same government. <br>
The district or locality in which such a group lives. <br>
<br>
2. A group of people having common interests: the scientific community; the international business community. <br>
A group viewed as forming a distinct segment of society: the gay community; the community of color. <br>
<br>
3. Similarity or identity: a community of interests. <br>
Sharing, participation, and fellowship. <br>
4Society as a whole; the public. <br>
Ecology. <br>
A group of plants and animals living and interacting with one another in a specific region under relatively similar environmental conditions. <br>
The region occupied by a group of interacting organisms. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
[Middle English communite, citizenry, from Old French, from Latin commnits, fellowship, from commnis, common. See common.]<br>
