<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp So far your post seems off base imo.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Rephrase: Respect the RTA Rules (in General), and wait a year or so to see the higher content. All that time losing members of your guild to the higher end guilds who have surpased that content, and are the ones enforcing the &quot;RTA Rules&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
Do you have any idea how many members my guild has lost because of this? I think I've lost count ... And each time someone has left, they have wound up going to ... Gues what , another guild thats farther along in game than we are.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Your complaint is that you “lose” members to other guilds because your own guild doesn’t progress fast enough.  What does that have to do with the RTA rules?  Suddenly, if you didn’t follow the RTA rules, your new, high-octane killing machine of a guild would roll up the server eating up all the content in its way?  I respectfully disagree.  The reason any particular guild can’t progress is for a variety of reasons, but none of them are linked to sharing rotations.  If we suddenly disbanded the rotations, your theory is you’re your guild would suddenly be able to kill Rallos Zek, High Priest of Ssra, and North ToV?  I don’t think so.  What would happen is those guilds that can already beat those encounters quickly and easily would farm those first, then go to content “safe” from others.  <br>
<br>
Additionally, do you think only the lower end guilds lose people?  BOTS loses people, mostly to ebay, but a few go to other guilds or server transfer.  Tindi and NB lose people, to BOTS, ebay, server transfers, plain ole burnout, etc.  It’s no different at the high end of the game than it is at the mid or low-end range.  As a fellow guild leader I can sympathize with losing people – but ignoring or breaking with the rotation system isn’t the solution, nor even the problem.<br>
<br>
Xedd’s quote was about PoP high end content, which isn’t the same as a guild who would see N ToV or Sleepers Tomb as new content.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> How exactly do you compete with that ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You don’t.  You have to recruit people that want the same thing you do – a place to hang their hat and help build.  Avoid the fast trackers, as they will only leave sooner or later anyway.  Some people want the instant gratification of jumping on the bandwagon of the success of others, and other people prefer to get there contributing alongside their long-term friends.  I remember one quote when Yattalren left NB for BOTS, and it stuck with me – “I’d rather be with NB on our first AoW kill than with BOTS on their 33rd Vulak kill.”  Choose loyal people who are after the same thing you are, and be prepared for even some of those to change their views over time (some always will).  Yattalren joined BOTS because NB didn’t raid for three days in a row one week.  Yattalren went to BOTS, had his fun, and now no longer plays to my knowledge.  We’re still here and progressing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Anyone want to try and tell me that that is consistant ? Which one Applies ...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No lack of consistency here.  We used to have 3-4 Euro guilds, who would start (at the time the only high end content), Fear and Hate in the early AM.  SoT, RF, VoF, and some others I am forgetting.  Those two rules were set up out of consideration for the fact Fear and Hate had long spawn times, and if US guilds weren’t careful, and were trying to get two clearings in, could wind up hurting the raids of a euro guild.  The problem lay as follows:  US guild goes in at 9 am PST, Fear repopped at the time in like 14-18 hours, and the zone would repop at 11 PM PST.  Guild clears it again by 2 AM, and now the euro guild might not have the numbers on to clear Fear (or Hate) the next day because nothing spawns until too late.  The 2 AM cutoff was because we had to have an actual drop dead time.  The clean-up section was because some euro and EST guilds would leave some mobs up, and other guilds would go in and clean up.  These two in tandem would try and cover both ends of the issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I call Hogwash ... I won't quote it again ... but FFA/FCFS means any and all guilds ... NOT all guilds except posting entities.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Call Hogwash all you want.  Non-posting entities that have no rotations aren’t covered in any of our rules, since they don’t follow them anyway.  Neither of those rules were about people like good ole Xenth or Janacy (I know I am misspelling the name, but I am sure someone knows who I am speaking of).  FCFS/FFA does mean any guilds, so anyone can go into Fear or Hate once the current guild leaves and says they are done for the day, or are no longer online to ask.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Hypothetical:<br>
Yes my guild is on Rotation for Sev and Trak, thus basically reserving that Mob for us ... Yet we can't reserve Hate, Fear , or Sky ...<br>
<br>
again I say, where is the Logic ??<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The logic is that those guilds who can kill Sev with less than 40 people, probably can’t use the gear from Hate/Fear.  Additionally, those who need epic pieces and can clear Fear or Hate with one group, can handle going on any of the ubiquitous unreserved nights during the week.  If your guild can handle Kunark or Velious content with incredibly low numbers, I hope you aren’t trying to say you need a full Saturday to clear Fear or Hate.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Next You have Rotations, which are in existance that Have 15 or 20+ Guilds on them. Thats one Kill everyone 3 - 4 months. How exactly is that fair ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Be careful of getting what you ask for.  The more people that want something, the more you need sharing, not less.  If no one wants THO, why have a rotation for it?  If 40 people want Sev, you need him on rotation, or the quick and the strong are who will monopolize the spawn.  If you take Sev off rotation, and the larger guilds can kill him with a single group or less, how often do you think you are going to find him up?  The green scale sells for 60k, haste cloaks and belts 30-60k as well.  You don’t think an idle group of Tindi or BOTS or NB at 2 am won’t run over and smack him down for the chance of an easy 100k plat?  And I’m not talking about a guild directive of “We need Sevs”, just an xp group hearing things like the old days of “LODI’S UP, GATE GATE GATE” and Lodi (or in this case Sev) is dead 10 minutes later.  It’s simple math, which is better, zero Sevs per year, or 4 per year?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Some of the Rotations , are Full , and Obsolete...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Full rotations means lots of people want the content, and thus we need formalized sharing.  You call Trak obsolete, I say he’s the only way to get VP keys.  You take him off rotation, and I promise you, Trak would be spawn camped by guilds who want to finish off their VP keys.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The Big Guilds of the Server ... Are seeing their EXP holes for regular EXP or AA threatened ... They are seeing their Cash Cow zones also being threatened, as people other than them will have access to the same zones as they do, and might just might sell whatever drop it may be for something cheaper than they would. This might be a little unfair , but this is how the thread is coming across to me...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, HoH and other zones are not “cash cows”, as there are far too many guilds with access to these zones.  The concern is about people who either don’t know what they are doing or with grief chips on their shoulders, ruining the progression through these zones for other people.  Guilds that are working their way up on their own are so far have been very considerate of clearing out when an area they are using for xp is needed for a flagging event.  Members of those guilds who haven’t gotten in on their own, seem to throw out the “but I was xp camping here first” argument.  Well, as much as you want to claim HoH is “an exp zone”, those three crypts are, first and foremost, the ONLY way to progress to get to Mith Marr and the Elemental Planes.  You can xp anywhere, I can only do HoH trials in three specific crypts.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Yet Everytime ... and I mean EVERYTIME , someone mentions the fact that the RTA rules are obsolete, and need to be reworked for the game as It is today , not the game as it was 3 years ago ... People call this excuse .. <br>
<br>
Hypocrits ... Bunch of lousy Hypocrits ... <br>
<br>
If this server is really More &quot;Civilized&quot; and More &quot;Mature&quot; than other servers ... Then running away from the need to re-examine Rules that were made close to 3 years ago, and hiding behind the excuse of FFA Chaos is nothing more than a Political Maneuver to help ensure that your Guild stays on top, cause you know the game has massively changed , and the current Rules are more of a hinderance than they are a benefit... But hey your guild doesn't have to worry about it ... Your already past that... <br>
<br>
If this server is Indeed more &quot;Civilized&quot; and more &quot;Mature&quot; then this suggestion wouldn't scare so many people ... because people would continue to act &quot;civilized&quot; and &quot;Mature&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It has nothing whatsoever to do with hypocrisy.  It has to do with the truth and being pragmatic.  What the RTA consists of, at its most basic level, is the compromise of what the high end and low end guilds find acceptable or reasonable.  No they are not obsolete, they are every bit as relevant today as they were when they were started.  Quite simply, the more people interested *and* capable of killing the content, the more necessary sharing on a formalized basis is.  You make the mistake of thinking Hate/Fear RESERVATIONS for mob ROTATIONS.  They are not the same thing.  Second, you get rid of the “Civilization” and “Maturity” the RTA represents, you need to be very realistic about what the consequences are.  That is all everyone is saying.  We’re not more mature or civilized because somehow the Rathe happened to have the 5,000 Everquest players who most closely emulate Mother Teresa.  We are more mature and civilized because we have the RTA, and (for the most part) all agree to a certain set of conventions.  If you remove the benefit for adhering to those conventions, you can forget expecting others to restrict themselves to following them.  If there is no longer any benefit for Tindi to share content, knowing we now have an FCFS or FFA server, then it seeks to protect itself, this is only logical.  What better way to protect itself, than to permakill the lowest end content it cares about – which at this point would be Rallos or maybe Behemoth.  Then NB follows suit, and permakills Aerin Dar, until we can find Rallos up enough times to beat him.  Then LoM does the same with Ssra mobs, making sure no one so much as sees one of these as long as that mob spawns in their raiding hours, etc etc.  Now you have the same stratification you see on other servers. . .why?  Because you got rid of the very thing that makes us different than other servers.  That isn’t hypocrisy, it’s the crux of the whole issue.  If you remove any benefit (i.e. knowledge that I don’t touch your stuff, and you won’t touch my stuff, out of turn), then you will, slowly or quickly depending on events, slowly devolve this server into a clone of every other – with all the resultant turf wars.  In an FFA/FCFS system, the nice guy who stands aside for others, loses out on advancement.<br>
<br>
The reason it gets brought up, is that unlike on other servers, guilds are allowed to progress far easier than they would under an FCFS system.  People who started playing this game after the rotations came into being, and started on the Rathe, or who emigrate here, seem to forget that when asking for “Compromise”, what the higher end guilds have already compromised.  The age old adage of someone having been offered an inch, asks for a mile.  People who throw out the “PnP SOE rules don’t say we can’t team”, and completely ignore the obvious “But they also don’t say I can’t permakill the mob”.  <br>
<br>
So the big guilds agree to the RTA, because the system, while not ideal for their interests, is workable.  The smaller ones agree to it, realizing that FFA EQ is very much a case of the rich get richer syndrome, and knowing the rotations they get on will be likewise protected.  Put yourself in BOTS shoes for a second.  Would you want Quellious-style public flaggings for the Elemental planes, after spending months of hard work to get where you are?  It’s not against SOE rules. . .however, SOE reworked how many flags you can get per mob, so they obviously DO have a problem with it.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> However, that Doesn't mean that We have to live with the rules that are already in existance, and are a hinderance to us, without at least trying to get them changed to something that is A)more feasable for us , and B) More feasable for the other Smaller Guilds on the Server ...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They are a hindrance to us as well.  If I could just hog the content I really care about for a very short time, say 1 month of all ST key droppers, one month of Trak, and HP/Cursed/Emp for two months, I would never need to touch them again and could only look forward.  Obviously I can’t, and shouldn’t be able to.  It wouldn’t be fair to other people.  The more interest you have in a mob, the more it needs rotating, not less.  As for your issue with guilds being “on” a rotation, but on autopass, I don’t understand it.  Very rarely have I ever seen a guild come back and start killing again, and the system doesn’t ever list them as up.  Why is it an issue?  However, if BOTS wanted to kill Trak again, you honestly think they would have sufficient trouble to merit “proving” they can?  I don’t.<br>
